      {
        "id": "n6",
        "type": "canvasNode",
        "position": {
          "x": 1591.4481321461037,
          "y": 66.49078550911027
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Python Code",
          "category": "processing",
          "blockType": "python_code",
          "inputs": [
            {
              "id": "in_0",
              "label": "in_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "outputs": [
            {
              "id": "out_0",
              "label": "out_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "defaultParameters": {
            "code": "# ---- Antenna beamwidths from physical dimensions ----\ntheta_az = lam / La           # azimuth (along-track) beamwidth [rad]\ntheta_rg = lam / Lr           # range (elevation) beamwidth [rad]\n\ndef antenna_pattern(squint):\n    return np.sinc(squint / theta_az) ** 2\n\ndef antenna_pattern_2d(az_ang, rg_ang):\n    return np.sinc(az_ang / theta_az) ** 2 * np.sinc(rg_ang / theta_rg) ** 2\n\nprint('antenna: theta_az=%.4f deg, theta_rg=%.4f deg' % (np.rad2deg(theta_az), np.rad2deg(theta_rg)))\n\n# ---- 2-D radiation pattern as a 3D surface (same Three.js helper) ----\n# equal angular span on both axes so the narrow azimuth beam vs the wider\n# range beam is read honestly.\nang_max = 3 * max(theta_az, theta_rg)\n_az = np.linspace(-ang_max, ang_max, 240)\n_rg = np.linspace(-ang_max, ang_max, 240)\nAZ, RG = np.meshgrid(_az, _rg)\nG = antenna_pattern_2d(AZ, RG)              # linear power 0..1\n# surface3d takes 20*log10(|field|); pass sqrt(G) so dB = 10*log10(G) (power dB)\nsurface3d(np.sqrt(G), np.rad2deg(_az), np.rad2deg(_rg),\n          'Antenna 2-D radiation pattern',\n          xlabel='azimuth angle [deg]', ylabel='range angle [deg]')\n",
            "label": "Antenna",
            "spec": "REAL HW: antenna pattern shapes the illumination. Characteristics (mindmap): range direction, azimuth direction, gain.\n\nSimulation: azimuth pattern modeled as normalized-sinc^2 with first null at the beamwidth theta_a:\n  pat(squint) = sinc(squint/theta_a)^2\nThis is a first-null beamwidth approximation (NOT 3 dB). Range-direction pattern and absolute gain are not modeled (relative pattern only)."
          },
          "codeCollapsed": true,
          "executionOrder": 13
        },
        "width": 400,
        "style": {}
      },
      {
        "id": "n7",
        "type": "canvasNode",
        "position": {
          "x": 2155.3781016214944,
          "y": 232.4712830444718
        },
        "data": {
          "label": "Python Code",
          "category": "processing",
          "blockType": "python_code",
          "inputs": [
            {
              "id": "in_0",
              "label": "in_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "outputs": [
            {
              "id": "out_0",
              "label": "out_0",
              "portType": "any"
            }
          ],
          "defaultParameters": {
            "code": "# Reflection / Raw Echo — point targets + (optional) ground clutter.\n# sar-visualizer parity: clutter scatterers are ordinary reflectors that flow\n# through the SAME echo kernel as the point targets, so they get the same\n# range+azimuth compression gain and survive focusing as coherent speckle\n# (unlike the LNA's incoherent thermal noise, which sinks under processing gain).\n#\n# Display window: 0-centred box of half-extent PEAK_HALF * view_scale. Point\n# targets: T1 at centre, the rest seeded-random inside +/-0.85*half. Clutter:\n# clutter_n scatterers uniform over +/-half with circular-complex-Gaussian\n# reflectivity, scale 10^(clutter_rcs_db/20) vs the unit point target. The\n# clutter_n / clutter_rcs_db GUI sliders drive this (n=0 -> no clutter).\nTARGET_SEED  = 42\nCLUTTER_SEED = 2\nhalf = PEAK_HALF * view_scale\n\n# Point targets carry unit reflectivity (1+0j); represent every source as\n# (name, az, slant, re_re, re_im) so the one echo loop handles both kinds.\nsources = [(n, a, s, 1.0, 0.0) for (n, a, s) in\n           make_point_targets(n_targets, half, half, TARGET_SEED, R0)]\n\ndef make_clutter_scatterers(count, rcs_db, half_az_m, half_range_m, seed, R0):\n    \"\"\"sar-visualizer makeClutterScatterers: `count` scatterers uniform over the\n    patch, each with circular complex Gaussian reflectivity (Box-Muller),\n    per-component sigma = 10^(rcs_db/20)/sqrt(2) so |reflectivity| std equals the\n    10^(rcs_db/20) scale relative to the unit point target.\"\"\"\n    rnd = make_rand(seed)\n    sigma = (10.0 ** (rcs_db / 20.0)) / np.sqrt(2.0)\n    out = []\n    for i in range(int(count)):\n        az_m = (rnd() * 2 - 1) * half_az_m\n        sr_m = R0 + (rnd() * 2 - 1) * half_range_m\n        u1 = max(rnd(), 1e-12); u2 = rnd()\n        mag = sigma * np.sqrt(-2.0 * np.log(u1))\n        re_re = mag * np.cos(2 * np.pi * u2)\n        re_im = mag * np.sin(2 * np.pi * u2)\n        out.append(('clutter%d' % i, az_m, sr_m, re_re, re_im))\n    return out\n\nn_clutter = int(clutter_n)\nif n_clutter > 0:\n    sources += make_clutter_scatterers(n_clutter, clutter_rcs_db, half, half, CLUTTER_SEED, R0)\n\nprint('sources: %d point + %d clutter  window=+/-%.0f m' % (n_targets, n_clutter, half))\n\ns_raw = np.zeros((Na, Nr), dtype=np.complex64)\nfor name, az_t, sr_t, gre, gim in sources:\n    R_eta  = np.sqrt(sr_t**2 + (az_pos - az_t)**2)        # (Na,)\n    tau    = 2 * R_eta / c\n    squint = np.arctan2(az_pos - az_t, sr_t)\n    pat    = antenna_pattern(squint)                      # (Na,)\n    dt     = t_r[None, :] - tau[:, None]                  # (Na,Nr)\n    rect   = (np.abs(dt) <= Tp/2).astype(np.float32)\n    phase  = np.pi * Kr * dt**2 - 4 * np.pi * R_eta[:, None] / lam\n    refl   = np.complex64(gre + 1j * gim)                 # 1+0j for point targets\n    s_raw += (refl * pat[:, None] * rect * np.exp(1j * phase)).astype(np.complex64)\n\nprint('raw echo: shape=%s dtype=%s  peak|s|=%.1f' % (s_raw.shape, s_raw.dtype, np.abs(s_raw).max()))\n",
            "label": "Reflection / Raw Echo",
            "spec": "Generate the raw SAR echo: transmit chirp reflects off point targets and returns with range delay.\n\nPhysics (per target, faithful to the prototype):\n  R_eta  = sqrt(sr^2 + (az_pos - az_t)^2)     hyperbolic range history\n  tau    = 2*R_eta / c                         two-way delay\n  squint = atan2(az_pos - az_t, sr)\n  pat    = antenna_pattern(squint)             (from Antenna block)\n  dt     = t_r - tau ; rect = |dt| <= Tp/2\n  phase  = pi*Kr*dt^2 - 4*pi*R_eta/lam         range chirp + carrier\n  s_raw += pat * rect * exp(j*phase)\n\nThis is the simulator's combined transmit->reflect->receive step (the real chain's UpConvert/XPA/RF-BPF are folded into the ideal baseband+carrier model)."
          },
          "executionOrder": 14,
          "codeCollapsed": true
        },
        "width": 400,
        "style": {}
      },
      {
